# Approach
Initialize two variables, first and last, to store the indices of the first and last occurrences of the target element. Initially, set them to -1, indicating that no occurrences have been found yet.

Use binary search to find the first occurrence of the target element:

Initialize left to 0 and right to nums.size() - 1.
While left is less than or equal to right, do the following:
Calculate the middle index mid as (left + right) / 2.
If nums[mid] is equal to the target element, update first to mid and search in the left half by setting right = mid - 1.
If nums[mid] is less than the target element, set left = mid + 1.
If nums[mid] is greater than the target element, set right = mid - 1.
Use binary search to find the last occurrence of the target element:

Reset left to 0 and right to nums.size() - 1.
While left is less than or equal to right, do the following:
Calculate the middle index mid as (left + right) / 2.
If nums[mid] is equal to the target element, update last to mid and search in the right half by setting left = mid + 1.
If nums[mid] is less than the target element, set left = mid + 1.
If nums[mid] is greater than the target element, set right = mid - 1.
After both binary searches are complete, first and last will hold the indices of the first and last occurrences of the target element, respectively.

Return the pair [first, last] as the result.

This approach ensures that you efficiently find the first and last occurrences of the target element in the sorted array using binary search.
