**Lower_bound returns an iterator pointing to the 1st element which is greater than equal to the given number (say x)
Upper_bound returns an iterator pointing to the 1st element which is just greater than the given number (say x)**

**to convert the iterator to index we subtract 1st iterator from them
(for vector we do minus vector_name.begin() and for array we do minus array_name)**

**example ->
vector v1{5, 7, 7, 8, 8, 10};
given number x=7**

**lowerbound - v1.begin() will return 1 (1st elemnt which is not less then 7 which is 7 it self) --> v1[1] = 7
upperbound - v1.begin() while return 3 (1st element which is just greater then 7 which is 8) --> v1[3] = 8
thats why we did upperbound - v1.begin() - 1 (to get last index of given number) --> v1[2] = 7
answer for the example will be {1,2}**
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> searchRange(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        auto low = lower_bound(nums.begin(),nums.end(),target);
        auto up = upper_bound(nums.begin(),nums.end(),target);

        if(!binary_search(nums.begin(),nums.end(),target))    return {-1,-1};       // If target is not present in the array

        int rock = low - nums.begin();
        int lee = up - nums.begin()-1;

        return {rock,lee};
    }
};
