**APPROACH 1 -** 2 Pointers - Time Complexity = **O(N)**:

*Take an array of size 2 **`res []`** to store the result and initialize both the cells with **-1**.*

1. Take 2 pointers - **ptr1** and **ptr2** starting from **0** and **N-1** respectively.
2. Iterate until **`ptr1 <= ptr2`**.
3. If **`nums [ptr1] == target`**:  set **`res [0] = ptr1`**, else increment **ptr1**.
4. If **`nums [ptr2] == target`**:  set **`res [1] = ptr2`**, else decrement **ptr2**.
5. If **`res [0] > -1`** and **`res [1] > -1`**, means we have found the indices, so break and return **res**.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] searchRange(int[] nums, int target) {
        int res [] = new int [2];
        res [0] = -1;
        res [1] = -1;
        if (nums.length == 0)
            return res;
        int ptr1 = 0, ptr2 = nums.length - 1;
        while (ptr1 <= ptr2) {
            if (nums [ptr1] == target)
                res [0] = ptr1;
            else
                ptr1++;
            if (nums [ptr2] == target)
                res [1] = ptr2;
            else
                ptr2--;
            if (res [0] > -1 && res [1] > -1)
                break;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

**APPROACH 2 -** Binary Search + Iteration - Time Complexity = **O(N)**:

*Take an array of size 2 **`res []`** to store the result and initialize both the cells with **-1**.*

1. Apply binary search and find a **possible** index of **target**.
2. Start from this index towards the left of the array and find the final index containing **target**. Set **res [0]** to this index.
3. Start from this index towards the right of the array and find the final index containing **target**. Set **res [1]** to this index.
4. If the target was not found in the initial Binary Search, return **res** as it is.
5. Return **res**.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] searchRange(int[] nums, int target) {
        int res [] = new int [2];
        res [0] = -1;
        res [1] = -1;
        if (nums.length == 0)
            return res;
        return BinarySearch (nums, target);
    }

    public int [] BinarySearch (int arr [], int target) {
        int l = 0, r = arr.length - 1, mid = -1;
        boolean flag = false;
        while (l <= r) {
            mid = l + (r - l) / 2;
            if (arr [mid] == target) {
                flag = true;
                break;
            }
            if (arr [mid] < target)
                l = mid + 1;
            else
                r = mid - 1;
        }
        int res [] = new int [2];
        if (flag == false) {
            res [0] = -1;
            res [1] = -1;
        }
        else {
            int i = mid;
            while (i > 0 && arr [i-1] == arr [i])
                i--;
            res [0] = i;
            i = mid;
            while (i < arr.length - 1 && arr [i] == arr [i+1])
                i++;
            res [1] = i;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

**APPROACH 3 -** Binary Search - Time Complexity = **O(log N)**:

`Credit: Mazhar_MIK's solution - https://leetcode.com/problems/find-first-and-last-position-of-element-in-sorted-array/discuss/1181941/C%2B%2B-(Two-approaches-O(logn)-with-comments)`

Basically, we will do the iteration part of Approach 2 in the Binary Search function itself.

1. Find first position of **target** using Binary Search. After finding target, **keep going towards left** until you find the final index. See the comments in the code.
2. Find last position of **target** using Binary Search. After finding target, **keep going towards right** until you find the final index. See the comments in the code.
3. Return **res** with these indices.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] searchRange(int[] nums, int target) {
        if (nums == null || nums.length == 0)
            return new int [] {-1, -1};
        int first = findFirst (nums, target);
        int last = findLast (nums, target);
        return new int [] {first, last};
    }

    public int findFirst (int arr [], int target) {
        int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1, mid = 0, res = -1;
        while (left <= right) {
            mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
            if (arr [mid] == target) {
                res = mid;                 // Possibly our solution
                right = mid - 1;           // But, still keep looking towards the left
            }
            else if (target > arr [mid])
                left = mid + 1;
            else
                right = mid - 1;
        }
        return res;
    }

    public int findLast (int arr [], int target) {
        int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1, mid = 0, res = -1;
        while (left <= right) {
            mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
            if (arr [mid] == target) {
               res = mid;                 // Possibly our solution
               left = mid + 1;            // But, still keep looking towards the right
            }
            else if (target > arr [mid])
                left = mid + 1;
            else
                right = mid - 1;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

