solutions.content:
Move forward until reach an appropriate staring point.

Q: What is an appropriate staring point? 
A: where the gas[i]>=cost[i]

Start from this point and move forward and check if there is any chance to loop and reach the same index. In case of negative result in the middle, lets update the moving index by the location where the condition is not satisfying (where we have no more gas to move forward).
This is because if on way of moving from source we are locked at location SKIP then there is no way to start from any points between source and location SKIP.
For example in following example, our candidates are the bolded ones. By starting from candidate index 1 (gas[1]=4, cost[1]=2), we stop at location 4 (gas[4]=5 , cost[4]=7 ); so there is no need to check the index 3 (gas[3]=4 , cost[4])

gas= [1,**4**,3,**4**,5,**5**]
cost = [3,**2**,4,**4**,7,**2**]

With simple optimization, we can skip many previously calculation, in my case my running time reduced from ~160ms to 4 ms


```
class Solution {
public:
    int canCompleteCircuit(vector<int>& gas, vector<int>& cost) {
      int s= gas.size();     
      for (int idx=0; idx< s;++idx) {            
          if (gas[idx]<cost[idx]) /* in starting point we should have gas[i]>=cost[i]*/
              continue;

          int cnt=0;
          int cap =0;
          for (cnt=0;cnt<s;++cnt) {
              int i = (idx+cnt)%s ;
              cap+= gas[i]-cost[i];
              if (cap<0) {
              /*if the there is no result till index i, lets skip all elements between idx and i. However if (i<idx) means ther ei sno result since we have already checked elements less than idx */    
                 if(i<idx)
                     return -1;
                  else
                    idx=i;
                  break;
              }
          }
          if(cnt==s)
              return idx;

      }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

