# Approach
- As soon as a gas station changed to -ve, our brute-force simulation began. The first step is to stop and proceed to the next station. But in order for us to see why, this is ineffective. We must examine the causes of car stops.
- Let's assume for the sake of this example that the car starts at 0 and can reach 3 gas stations. And after attempting to reach the fourth station, its gas runs out.
Once the brute force approach realises it can complete the journey, it restarts the simulation from this gas station. However, this upcoming simulation is pointless and a waste of time.

- The failure of these three gas stations and journeys is previously known. This indicates that, when comparing our fuel buildup to our gasoline use, we were either in some sort of surplus or, at the absolute least, breaking even, with precisely enough fuel to complete every journey.
- This is due to the fact that if we were in some sort of deficit, our car would have already consumed gas earlier. This indicates that we were in some sort of deficit on the previous trip since we ran out of petrol.
As a result, neither Index 1 nor Index 2 nor Index 3 can be reached because we cannot begin the journey at the very beginning.

- In terms of our algorithm, this means that we will be aware if we run out of fuel, say at a gas station. Each and every gas station between it and the starting point is a poor starting point.
- As a result, we can begin our efforts at the next petrol station on the i + 1 station. So perhaps you now have a better understanding of how this O(N) solution will work.
