solutions.content:
**Pattern**: Cumulative sum pattern

Similar to Kadane's algorithm. The below intution of using cumulative sums of continuous positive balance could be easily arrived at by thinking bruteforce first (where for each index cumulative balance is computed) and realizing to reduce this O(n^2) to O(n) can be done by storing the cumulative sum of balance in 1 travesal and using it to find the solution.

**Intution**
1. The total gas (gas means gas at each station) should atleast match upto toal cost (cost means gas required to reach next station) for any successful travel.
2. If current balance (balance means gas at current station - gas required to next station) is negative we can't travel to next station. So current station will never be the starting station.
3. So a positive curent balance be a starting station, but is ithat always true? A group of consequtive positive balances can be collectively negated by a bigger negative current balance. 
4.  **A powerful observation in continuation to above observation is none of the stations at each of the positive balances can be a starting point now**. And since the current balance is negative, even current station can't be starting station. Now the only possibility for a possible starting station is the next station, but we still have to repeat the process of checking if it has negative balance or if any negative balance in future negates all the positive balances starting from it.
5.  Observations 2 and 4 can be clubbed together during implementation.
6.  Another observation is even if positive balances consequetively occur till last station, we have to make sure they totally exceed all the previous negative and positive balances atleast by 0 for observation 1 to be true. (Ok, I think this is a redundant statement of observation 1.)

**Note**:
[A post on why this is tagged as a "Greedy" problem](https://leetcode.com/problems/gas-station/discuss/1004074/Greedy-Method-or-Explanation-+-Visual-or-Python) 

**Code**:
```
// Got accepeted submission without any compile or runtime errors in the first try!
class Solution {
    public int canCompleteCircuit(int[] gas, int[] cost) {
        int n = gas.length;
        int balance = 0;
        int negativeSum = 0;
        int possibleStart = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            balance += gas[i] - cost[i];
            if (balance < 0) {
                negativeSum += balance;
                possibleStart = i + 1;
                balance = 0;
            }
        }

        if (possibleStart == n) {
            return -1;
        }
        if (balance >= Math.abs(negativeSum)) return possibleStart;
        return -1;
    }
}
```
```
/*

gas:            1 2 3 0 3
