It seems for me that there lacks the complete mathematical proof of the O(n) solution, so I want to share my thoughts here.

Let total = (gas[0] - cost[0]) + (gas[1] - cost[1]) + ... + (gas[N] - cost[N]). If total >= 0, then there must exist at least one j, where 0 <= j <= N, that sum(j, N) = (gas[j] - cost[j]) + ... + (gas[N] - cost[N]) >= 0 without any place being negative. In other words, there mush be a gas station j that if we start from it, we can arrive at the first station. Let j represents the first station satisfies this property. Then there are k blocking points, where 0 <= b1 < b2 < ... < bk <= j - 1, 1 <= k <= j, such that the sum between (0, b1), (b1, b2), ..., (bk-1, bk) are negative. Then we have total = sum(0, b1) + ... + sum(bk-1, bk) + sum(j, N). When total >= 0, we have sum(j, N) >= -sum(0, b1) + ... + -sum(bk-1, bk), based on the definition, we can infer that we can go from j to j.

So after the proof, the algorithm and code just come naturally:

    public int canCompleteCircuit(int[] gas, int[] cost) {
        if (gas == null || cost == null || gas.length != cost.length) return -1;
        if (gas.length == 0) return -1;
        int total = 0, sum = 0, diff = 0;
        int start = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < gas.length; i++) {
            diff = gas[i] - cost[i];
            if ((sum += diff) < 0) {
                start = i + 1;
                sum = 0;
            }
            total += diff;
        }
        return total >= 0 ? start : -1;
    }

